            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>How this brick calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This brick calculator estimates how many bricks and how much
                mortar you need for a wall or partition. It also lets you
                include openings (doors, windows), wall thickness, waste
                allowance, and optional cost per brick and mortar bag.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Wall area</h3>
              <p>
                The calculator first finds the net wall area to be covered with
                bricks:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Gross wall area</strong></p>
                <p>\( A_\text{gross} = L \times H \)</p>
                <p>where:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\( L \) = wall length</li>
                  <li>\( H \) = wall height</li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                  <strong>Openings area</strong> (sum of all doors and windows):
                </p>
                <p>\( A_\text{openings} = \sum (w_i \times h_i) \)</p>
                <p><strong>Net wall area</strong>:</p>
                <p>\( A_\text{net} = A_\text{gross} - A_\text{openings} \)</p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Brick coverage area</h3>
              <p>
                Each brick occupies a certain area on the wall, including mortar
                joints. For a standard stretcher bond, we use the brick length
                and height plus the joint thickness:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Brick module dimensions</strong></p>
                <p>\( L_b' = L_b + t_j \)</p>
                <p>\( H_b' = H_b + t_j \)</p>
                <p>where:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\( L_b \) = brick length</li>
                  <li>\( H_b \) = brick height</li>
                  <li>\( t_j \) = mortar joint thickness</li>
                </ul>
                <p><strong>Brick face area (including joint)</strong>:</p>
                <p>\( A_\text{brick} = L_b' \times H_b' \)</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The calculator converts all dimensions to a consistent unit
                (meters) internally, so you can mix feet, inches, and
                millimeters safely.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Number of bricks</h3>
              <p>
                The basic brick count is the net wall area divided by the area
                covered by one brick:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Bricks per wythe</strong> (single-brick thickness):
                </p>
                <p>\( N_\text{net} = \dfrac{A_\text{net}}{A_\text{brick}} \)</p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Adjust for wall thickness</strong> (multiple wythes):
                </p>
                <p>
                  \( N_\text{net,thick} = N_\text{net} \times n_\text{wythes} \)
                </p>
                <p>where \( n_\text{wythes} \) is 1, 1.5, or 2 bricks thick.</p>
                <p><strong>Include waste</strong>:</p>
                <p>
                  \( N_\text{total} = N_\text{net,thick} \times (1 + w/100) \)
                </p>
                <p>where \( w \) is the waste percentage.</p>
              </div>

              <h3>4. Mortar volume estimation</h3>
              <p>
                Mortar volume is estimated from the difference between the total
                wall volume and the volume of all bricks:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Wall volume</strong> (approximate):</p>
                <p>\( V_\text{wall} = A_\text{net} \times t_\text{wall} \)</p>
                <p>
                  where \( t_\text{wall} \) is the wall thickness (number of
                  brick widths × brick thickness).
                </p>
                <p><strong>Total brick volume</strong>:</p>
                <p>
                  \( V_\text{bricks} = N_\text{net,thick} \times V_\text{brick}
                  \)
                </p>
                <p><strong>Mortar volume</strong>:</p>
                <p>\( V_\text{mortar} = V_\text{wall} - V_\text{bricks} \)</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The tool then converts mortar volume to cubic feet, cubic
                meters, and an approximate number of 80 lb (36.3 kg) mortar
                bags.
              </p>

              <h3>Typical brick sizes</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>US modular brick:</strong> 7 5/8 × 2 1/4 × 3 5/8 in
                  (194 × 57 × 92 mm)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>US standard brick:</strong> 8 × 2 1/4 × 3 5/8 in (203
                  × 57 × 92 mm)
                </li>
                <li><strong>UK standard brick:</strong> 215 × 65 × 102.5 mm</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                You can also switch to <strong>Custom size</strong> and enter
                any brick dimensions you need.
              </p>

              <h2>Practical tips for ordering bricks and mortar</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Round brick counts <strong>up</strong> to the nearest full
                  pack or pallet as required by your supplier.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use <strong>higher waste (10–15%)</strong> for complex
                  patterns, many corners, or if bricks are fragile.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Order a little extra mortar, especially in hot or windy
                  conditions where it can dry out faster.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Always confirm local building code requirements for wall
                  thickness, ties, and reinforcement.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <!-- FAQ -->
            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>Brick calculator FAQ</h2>

              <h3>How do I calculate how many bricks I need?</h3>
              <p>
                Measure the wall length and height, subtract the area of any
                openings, then divide the net wall area by the area covered by
                one brick including mortar joints. This calculator automates all
                of that and also lets you add waste and wall thickness.
              </p>

              <h3>How much mortar do I need per 1,000 bricks?</h3>
              <p>
                For standard modular bricks with 3/8 in (10 mm) joints, a common
                rule of thumb is about
                <strong>7–8 cubic feet</strong> (0.20–0.23 m³) of mortar per
                1,000 bricks. The exact amount depends on your joint thickness
                and workmanship, so the calculator estimates mortar volume for
                your specific inputs.
              </p>

              <h3>What waste percentage should I use?</h3>
              <p>
                For simple straight walls, <strong>5–7%</strong> waste is
                usually enough. For more complex projects with many cuts,
                corners, or decorative patterns, <strong>10–15%</strong> is
                safer. The default 10% is a good starting point for most
                residential work.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I use this for blockwork or pavers?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. As long as you know the unit dimensions (length, height,
                thickness) and joint thickness, you can treat blocks or pavers
                as “bricks” in the calculator. Just be sure to select
                <strong>Custom size</strong> and enter the correct measurements.
              </p>

              <h3>Does this replace structural design?</h3>
              <p>
                No. This tool is for <strong>material estimation only</strong>.
                It does not check structural capacity, reinforcement, or code
                compliance. For load-bearing walls or critical structures,
                consult a qualified engineer or architect.
              </p>
